{
    "analysis": "From the previous file summaries: metric.csv is large and dominated by many node-6 container KPIs; trace.csv and error_logs.csv are concentrated on frontend pods; error_logs timestamps range (min 1647737332, max 1647737513) and all error entries are from frontend-0/1/2. This suggests at least one failure involved frontend pods in the timeframe where error_logs exist. To proceed methodically per the required workflow, we must (1) compute global thresholds (P95) for each metric time series (component-KPI) using the full metric.csv, and (2) then filter metric points to the incident window (March 20, 2022 08:30 to 09:00 in UTC+8) to find component-KPI series that exceed their global thresholds during the window. That will narrow candidate components and KPIs for further trace/log analysis. No threshold calculation has been done yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv. For every unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair compute the global P95 value of 'value' using the full available series (do NOT filter by time before computing P95). Then filter metric.csv to timestamps inside the incident window March 20, 2022 08:30:00 to 09:00:00 in UTC+8 (Executor should convert timestamps). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) that has at least one point in the incident window, compute: anomaly_count = number of points in the window with value > global_P95, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (smallest timestamp in window where value > P95), max_value_in_window, global_P95. Return the top 20 (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs with anomaly_count>0 sorted by anomaly_count descending. For each returned pair include fields: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, global_P95. Also return the total number of distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs that had anomaly_count>0. Limit rows to 20."
}

{
    "analysis": "Executor found 1,205 distinct (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs with values exceeding their global P95 during the incident window, with many top anomalies concentrated at 08:30–08:32 (UTC+8). The top anomalous KPIs include numerous frontend mesh metrics (frontend-0), several container network KPIs tied to node-5/node-6, and a few node-level KPIs (node-2 load.15, node-5 CPU). These anomalies are consecutive (anomaly_count=3), implying faults spanning multiple minutes starting at ~08:30–08:32. Error logs earlier were concentrated on frontend pods later in the window (timestamps ~1647737332–1647737513), suggesting a possible second failure later than the first metric burst. To localize the two separate failures we need a component-level aggregation of anomalies (how many distinct KPIs per component breached thresholds, earliest breach timestamp per component, and severity of breach) so we can prioritize candidates for trace and log correlation.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the global P95 thresholds already computed per (cmdb_id,kpi_name), aggregate anomaly information to the component (cmdb_id) level for the incident window March 20, 2022 08:30:00–09:00:00 (UTC+8). For each cmdb_id that has at least one anomalous (value>global_P95) datapoint in the window, compute: 1) distinct_kpi_count = number of distinct kpi_name with anomalies; 2) earliest_anomaly_timestamp = smallest timestamp in window where any KPI for this cmdb_id breached its P95; 3) max_breach_ratio = max over all anomalous points of (value / global_P95) for that cmdb_id; 4) top_kpis = up to 3 kpi_name values for this component with the largest max (value/global_P95) ratios (include their ratio). Restrict components to the set of possible root cause components (nodes, pods, and services listed in the diagnosis rules). Return the top 20 components sorted by distinct_kpi_count (desc), then by max_breach_ratio (desc). Provide fields: cmdb_id, distinct_kpi_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_breach_ratio, top_kpis (list of up to 3 {kpi_name, ratio}). Limit output rows to 20."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the last aggregation step we have: (1) a large, early anomaly burst starting ~1647736200 (2022-03-20 08:30:00 UTC+8) affecting many components (frontend-0/1/2, multiple service pods, node-5/node-6), and (2) error_logs exist later in the window with timestamps between 1647737332 and 1647737513 and are concentrated on frontend pods. This suggests two separate incidents: an early widespread metric anomaly cluster (around 08:30–08:32) and a later frontend-visible failure (around the error_logs timestamps). To localize root causes for each failure we must identify precise fault segments (consecutive anomalous minutes), their start times, durations, and severity for candidate components. Focusing on the most suspicious components (frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2 and node-5, node-6) will keep the search bounded and allow correlation with traces/logs next.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the global P95 thresholds already computed per (cmdb_id,kpi_name), analyze only the following components: frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, node-5, node-6. For each component, within the incident window March 20, 2022 08:30:00–09:00:00 (UTC+8), do the following:\n1) Retrieve all timestamps (minute-granular) where any KPI value for that component exceeded its global P95.\n2) Collapse these timestamps into consecutive-minute fault segments (continuous run of minutes). For each segment produce: start_timestamp, end_timestamp, duration_minutes, distinct_kpi_count_in_segment (number of distinct kpi_name that breached during the segment), and max_breach_ratio_in_segment (max of value/global_P95 across all breached points in the segment). \n3) For each component return up to the top 5 segments sorted by start_timestamp (earliest first). \nReturn a compact table with columns: component, start_timestamp, end_timestamp, duration_minutes, distinct_kpi_count_in_segment, max_breach_ratio_in_segment. Limit rows to at most 25 (5 components * up to 5 segments)."
}

